<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with developments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments in the earthquake that rocked
Northern California Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE QUAKE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake hit at 5:04 p.m. PDT, registering 6.9 on Richter
scale, and was centered on the San Andreas Fault about eight miles
northeast of Santa Cruz and 75 miles south of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   At least 272 people died, and 650 were injured. Of the dead, 253
were killed when the upper level of two-tiered Interstate 880 in
Oakland collapsed onto the lower level.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DAMAGE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The quake collapsed buildings, broke windows, and caused other
damage across nearly 100 miles.
   Severed gas lines started fires. One spectacular fire in San
Francisco burned a block of buildings and another damaged downtown
Berkeley.
   Power, telephone, water and other services were disrupted for at
least 1 million people.
   The San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge and two bridges near Santa
Cruz collapsed. The San Mateo and Dumbarton bridges were closed for
inspection.
   Highways were damaged and mountain passes outside Santa Cruz
were closed due to landslides and fissures in the roads.
   Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy said damages would total ``the better part
of $1 billion.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LOOTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Some looting was reported in San Francisco and in Los Gatos, a
town between San Jose and Santa Cruz, but no arrests were made.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed a disaster relief declaration for seven
counties in the Bay area and dispatched Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner to join Vice President Quayle in California to
assess damage.
   Military officials mobilized National Guard units to aid the
rescue.
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency set up a disaster field
office in The Presidio, an Army post in San Francisco.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney ordered the armed forces to set up
an emergency group to help coordinate aid efforts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WORLD REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union made an unprecedented offer of relief aid and
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev sent condolences in a telegram to
President Bush.
   Offers of aid came from the Philippines, Japan, France, Britain,
Switzerland and several other nations.
   Pope John Paul II was ``deeply saddened'' and praying for the
victims.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WORLD SERIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball fans awaiting the start of Game Three of the World
Series evacuated Candlestick Park, which sustained structural
damage. No major injuries were reported and there was no word on
when the game would be played.
</TEXT>
